# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: c-book
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:c-book/c-programming-code-style] This is a basic introduction to good coding style in the C Programming Language.
[src:c-book/c-programming-code-style] It is designed to provide information on how to effectively use indentation, comments, and other elements that will make your C code more readable.
[src:c-book/c-programming-code-style] It is not a tutorial on actual C programming.
[src:c-book/c-programming-code-style] As a beginning programmer, the point of creating structure in the program code might not be clear, as the compiler doesn't care about the difference.
[src:c-book/c-programming-code-style] However, as programs become complex, chances are that writing the program has become a joint effort.
[src:c-book/c-programming-code-style] (Or others might want to see how it was accomplished.
[src:c-book/c-programming-code-style] Or you may have to read it again years later.) Well-written code also helps you get an overview of what the code does.
[src:c-book/c-programming-code-style] In the following sections, we will attempt to explain good programming practices that will in turn make your programs clearer.
[src:c-book/c-programming-code-style] In C, programs are composed of statements.
[src:c-book/c-programming-code-style] Statements are terminated with a semi-colon, and are collected in sections known as functions.
[src:c-book/c-programming-code-style] The following block of code is essentially the same.
[src:c-book/c-programming-code-style] While it contains exactly the same code, and will compile and execute with the same result, the removal of spacing causes an essential difference: it's harder to read.
[src:c-book/c-programming-code-style] The simple use of indents and line breaks can greatly improve code readability without impacting code performance.
[src:c-book/c-programming-code-style] Readable code makes it much easier to see where functions and procedures end and which lines are part of which loops and procedures.
[src:c-book/c-programming-code-style] This lesson is going to focus on improving the coding style of an example piece of code which applies a formula and prints the result.
[src:c-book/c-programming-code-style] Later, you'll see how to write code for such tasks in more detail.
[src:c-book/c-programming-code-style] For now, focus on how the code looks, not what it does.
[src:c-book/c-programming-code-style] The addition of white space inside your code is arguably the most important part of good code structure.
[src:c-book/c-programming-code-style] Effective use of white space can create a visual scale of how your code flows, which can be very important when returning to your code when you want to maintain it.
[src:c-book/c-programming-code-style] Rather than putting everything on one line, it is much more readable to break up long lines so that each statement and declaration goes on its own line.
[src:c-book/c-programming-code-style] Blank lines should be used to offset the main components of your code.
[src:c-book/c-programming-code-style] The following lines of code have line breaks between functions, but without indentation.
[src:c-book/c-programming-code-style] But it's still not as readable as it can be.
[src:c-book/c-programming-code-style] Many text editors automatically indent appropriately when you hit the enter/return key.
[src:c-book/c-programming-code-style] Although adding simple line breaks between key blocks of code can make code easier to read, it provides no information about the block structure of the program.
[src:c-book/c-programming-code-style] Indentation visually separates paths of execution by moving their starting points to a new column.
[src:c-book/c-programming-code-style] This simple practice will make it much easier to read and understand code.
[src:c-book/c-programming-code-style] It is now fairly obvious as to which parts of the program fit inside which blocks.
[src:c-book/c-programming-code-style] You can tell which parts of the program the coder has intended to be conditional, and which ones he or she has not.
[src:c-book/c-programming-code-style] Although it might not be immediately noticeable, once many nested paths get added to the structure of the program, the use of indentation can be very important.
[src:c-book/c-programming-code-style] Thus, indentation makes the structure of your program clear.
[src:c-book/c-programming-code-style] It is claimed that research has shown that an indentation size between 2 to 4 characters is easier to read than 8 character indents.
[src:c-book/c-programming-code-style] However, an indent of 8 characters may still be in use for some systems.
[src:c-book/c-programming-code-style] This section is going to focus on the various uses of each form of commentary.
[src:c-book/c-programming-code-style] Single-line comments are most useful for simple 'side' notes that explain what certain parts of the code do.
[src:c-book/c-programming-code-style] The best places to put these comments are next to variable declarations, and next to pieces of code that may need explanation.
[src:c-book/c-programming-code-style] Comments should make clear the intention and ideas behind the corresponding code.
[src:c-book/c-programming-code-style] What is immediately obvious from reading the code does not belong in a comment.
[src:c-book/c-programming-code-style] Multi-line comments are most useful for long explanations of code.
[src:c-book/c-programming-code-style] They can be used as copyright/licensing notices, and they can also be used to explain the purpose of a block of code.
[src:c-book/c-programming-code-style] This can be useful for two reasons: They make your functions easier to understand, and they make it easier to spot errors in code.
[src:c-book/c-programming-code-style] If you know what a block is *supposed* to do, then it is much easier to find the piece of code that is responsible if an error occurs.
[src:c-book/c-programming-code-style] As an example, suppose we had a program that was designed to print "Hello, World!
[src:c-book/c-programming-code-style] " a certain number of lines, a specified number of times.
[src:c-book/c-programming-code-style] There would be many for loops in this program.
[src:c-book/c-programming-code-style] For this example, we shall call the number of lines *i*, and the number of strings per line as *j*.
[src:c-book/c-programming-code-style] This provides a good explanation of what *i'*s purpose is, whilst not going into detail of what *j* does.
[src:c-book/c-programming-code-style] By going into detail over what the specific path does (and not ones inside it), it will be easier to troubleshoot the path.
[src:c-book/c-programming-code-style] Similarly, you should always include a multi-line comment before each function, to explain the role, preconditions and postconditions of each function.
[src:c-book/c-programming-code-style] Always leave the technical details to the individual blocks inside your program - this makes it easier to troubleshoot.
[src:c-book/c-programming-code-style] This system allows for an at-a-glance explanation of what the function should do.
[src:c-book/c-programming-code-style] You can then go into detail over how each aspect of the program is achieved later on in the program.
[src:c-book/c-programming-code-style] This will allow any outside users of the program an easy way to comprehend what the code functions are and how they operate.
[src:c-book/c-programming-code-style] It also inhibits uncertainty with other like-named functions.
[src:c-book/c-programming-code-style] Comments written in source files can be used for documenting source code automatically by using popular tools like Doxygen.
[src:c-book/c-programming-variables] Like most programming languages, C uses and processes **variables**.
[src:c-book/c-programming-variables] In C, variables are human-readable names for the places where data used by a running program is stored.
[src:c-book/c-programming-variables] Imagine variables as placeholders for values, much like in mathematics.
[src:c-book/c-programming-variables] You can think of a variable as being equivalent to its assigned value.
[src:c-book/c-programming-variables] So, if you have a variable x with the value 4 , then it follows that $x+1=5$ .
[src:c-book/c-programming-variables] Before we can continue on this topic, though, we must first look at how C organizes memory.
[src:c-book/c-programming-variables] Literals and other constants (explained later) may be loaded and used directly by the compiled machine code, or they might be loaded from a read-only *data segment* in your program that is created during the build process.
[src:c-book/c-programming-variables] Where does the rest of the information for your program go?
[src:c-book/c-programming-variables] CPUs have a small number of low-capacity but high-speed *registers* for data storage.
[src:c-book/c-programming-variables] When you create a variable, your compiler will likely assign a register for it to live in while it exists.
[src:c-book/c-programming-variables] These registers are nowhere near large enough to contain all the information our programs need, though.
[src:c-book/c-programming-variables] Data is said to be *pushed* when it is added to the stack, and *popped* when it is removed.
[src:c-book/c-programming-variables] In this section, the variables we create will exist in CPU registers and the stack.
[src:c-book/c-programming-variables] Here is an example of declaring an integer, which we've called `some_number`.
[src:c-book/c-programming-variables] This statement tells the compiler to create a variable called `some_number` and associate it with a location in memory, either in a register (if there is room) or on the stack.
[src:c-book/c-programming-variables] We also tell the compiler the type of the data that will be stored there, in this case an `int` for integer.
[src:c-book/c-programming-variables] This lets the compiler know how much total memory to set aside for the data.
[src:c-book/c-programming-variables] On most modern machines, an `int` is 4 bytes in length.
[src:c-book/c-programming-variables] The above statement directs the compiler to insert an integer representation of the number 3 into the memory location associated with `some_number`.
[src:c-book/c-programming-variables] Variable names in C are made up of letters (upper and lower case), digits, and underscores (`_`).
[src:c-book/c-programming-variables] As the last example suggests, certain words are reserved as keywords in the language, and these cannot be used as variable names.
[src:c-book/c-programming-variables] When working with other developers, you should take steps to avoid using the same name for global variables or function names.
[src:c-book/c-programming-variables] Some large projects adhere to naming guidelines to avoid duplicate names and for consistency.
[src:c-book/c-programming-variables] There are certain sets of names that, while not language keywords, are reserved for one reason or another.
[src:c-book/c-programming-variables] For example, a C compiler might use certain names "behind the scenes", and this might cause problems for a program that attempts to use them.
[src:c-book/c-programming-variables] Also, some names are reserved for possible future use in the C standard library.
[src:c-book/c-programming-variables] The rules for determining exactly what names are reserved (and in what contexts they are reserved) are complex, and as a beginner you don't need to worry about them much anyway.
[src:c-book/c-programming-variables] For now, just avoid using names that begin with an underscore character.
[src:c-book/c-programming-variables] It is not allowed to use the same name for multiple variables in the same scope.
[src:c-book/c-programming-variables] It is possible to give a variable in an inner scope the same name as one defined in an outer scope.
[src:c-book/c-programming-variables] In that inner scope, and all scopes inside it, the reused name refers to the new variable.
[src:c-book/c-programming-variables] But, outside that scope, the name refers to the old variable, which remains unaffected by anything that happened in the inner scope.
[src:c-book/c-programming-variables] It's as if the outer variable is invisible while in the inner scope.
[src:c-book/c-programming-variables] We say that the outer variable has been *shadowed* by the inner variable.
[src:c-book/c-programming-variables] Let's look at an example to get a better idea of scope.
[src:c-book/c-programming-variables] When you write C programs, you may be tempted to write code that will depend on certain numbers.
[src:c-book/c-programming-variables] For example, you may be writing a program for a grocery store.
[src:c-book/c-programming-variables] This complex program has thousands upon thousands of lines of code.
[src:c-book/c-programming-variables] The programmer decides to represent the cost of a can of corn, currently 99 cents, as a literal throughout the code.
[src:c-book/c-programming-variables] Now, assume the cost of a can of corn changes to 89 cents.
[src:c-book/c-programming-variables] The programmer must now go in and manually change each entry of 99 cents to 89.
[src:c-book/c-programming-variables] While this is not that big a problem, considering the "global find-replace" function of many text editors, consider another problem: the cost of a can of green beans is also initially 99 cents.
[src:c-book/c-programming-variables] To reliably change the price, you have to look at every occurrence of the number 99.
[src:c-book/c-programming-variables] C possesses certain functionality to avoid these *magic numbers*.
[src:c-book/c-programming-variables] ...a programmer can simply change that constant and not have to worry about setting the value elsewhere.
[src:c-book/c-programming-variables] When the `const` qualifier is used, the declared variable must be initialized at declaration.
[src:c-book/c-programming-variables] Constants are useful for most than just having a single source of truth for some data.
[src:c-book/c-programming-variables] For one thing, many compilers can perform some small optimizations on data when it knows that data will never change.
[src:c-book/c-programming-variables] The compiler might decide that it would be more performant to avoid accessing memory to read the constant and instead copy the value of the constant throughout the compiled program.
[src:c-book/c-programming-variables] The two expressions above evaluate to the size of the object (or type) specified, in bytes.
[src:c-book/c-programming-variables] The return type is `size_t` (defined in the header `stddef.h`), which is an unsigned integer large enough to represent any possible object size.
[src:c-book/c-programming-variables] This is not a function; when your program is compiled, the expression is replaced with a constant number of bytes.
[src:c-book/c-programming-variables] The C standard does not set in stone the data type sizes described earlier, but your compiler knows how much space each type takes on your system, and uses that knowledge to replace uses of `sizeof`.
[src:c-book/c-programming-variables] When you declare a local variable as `static`, it is created just like any other variable.
[src:c-book/c-programming-variables] However, when the variable goes out of scope—the block it was local to exits—the variable stays in memory, retaining its value.
[src:c-book/c-programming-variables] The variable stays in memory until the program ends.
[src:c-book/c-programming-variables] While this behavior resembles that of global variables, static variables still obey scope rules and therefore cannot be accessed outside of their scope.
[src:c-book/c-programming-variables] This is called *static storage duration*.
[src:c-book/c-programming-variables] Variables declared `static` are initialized to zero by default.
[src:c-book/c-programming-variables] They can be initialized explicitly on declaration to any constant value.
[src:c-book/c-programming-variables] The initialization is made just once, at compile time.
[src:c-book/c-programming-variables] The `k` variables retain their value, but they are two different variables, one in each of their scopes.
[src:c-book/c-programming-variables] Included here, for completeness, are more of the modifiers that standard C provides.
[src:c-book/c-programming-variables] *volatile* is more of interest to advanced programmers.
[src:c-book/c-programming-variables] *register* is deprecated and generally not of interest to either beginning or advanced programmers.
[src:c-book/c-programming-variables] `**auto**` is a modifier which specifies an "automatic" variable that is automatically created when in scope and destroyed when out of scope.
[src:c-book/c-programming-variables] If you think this sounds like pretty much what you've been doing all along when you declare a variable, you're right: all declared items within a block are implicitly "automatic".
[src:c-book/c-programming-variables] For this reason, the *auto* keyword is more like the answer to a trivia question than a useful modifier, and there are lots of very competent programmers that are unaware of its existence.
[src:c-book/common-practices] With its extensive use, a number of common practices and conventions have evolved to help avoid errors in C programs.
[src:c-book/common-practices] These are simultaneously a demonstration of the application of good software engineering principles to a language and an indication of the limitations of C.
[src:c-book/common-practices] Although few are used universally, and some are controversial, each of these enjoys wide use.
[src:c-book/common-practices] Although one-dimensional arrays are easy to create dynamically using malloc, and fixed-size multidimensional arrays are easy to create using the built-in language feature, dynamic multidimensional arrays are trickier.
[src:c-book/common-practices] There are a number of different ways to create them, each with different tradeoffs.
[src:c-book/common-practices] Because of array-pointer interchangeability, you can index this just like static multidimensional arrays, i.e.
[src:c-book/common-practices] is the element at the 6th row and 3rd column.
[src:c-book/common-practices] For more information, see the comp.lang.c FAQ, question 6.16.
[src:c-book/common-practices] In some cases, the use of multi-dimensional arrays can best be addressed as an array of structures.
[src:c-book/common-practices] Before user-defined data structures were available, a common technique was to define a multi-dimensional array, where each column contained different information about the row.
[src:c-book/common-practices] This approach is also frequently used by beginner programmers.
[src:c-book/common-practices] For example, columns of a two-dimensional character array might contain last name, first name, address, etc.
[src:c-book/common-practices] In cases like this, it is better to define a structure that contains the information that was stored in the columns, and then create an array of pointers to that structure.
[src:c-book/common-practices] This is especially true when the number of data points for a given record might vary, such as the tracks on an album.
[src:c-book/common-practices] In these cases, it is better to create a structure for the album that contains information about the album, along with a dynamic array for the list of songs on the album.
[src:c-book/common-practices] Then an array of pointers to the album structure can be used to store the collection.
[src:c-book/common-practices] The index is slightly trickier than before, but can still be obtained by y*i+j.
[src:c-book/common-practices] Note that w*(x*(y*i+j)+k)+l is equal to w*x*y*i + w*x*j + w*k + l, but uses fewer operations (see Horner's Method).
[src:c-book/common-practices] It uses the same number of operations as accessing a static array by dim4[i][j][k][l], so should not be any slower to use.
[src:c-book/common-practices] The disadvantage is that it can be difficult at first to get used to how to index the elements.
[src:c-book/common-practices] In most object-oriented languages, objects cannot be created directly by a client that wishes to use them.
[src:c-book/common-practices] Instead, the client must ask the class to build an instance of the object using a special routine called a constructor.
[src:c-book/common-practices] Constructors are important because they allow an object to enforce invariants about its internal state throughout its lifetime.
[src:c-book/common-practices] Destructors, called at the end of an object's lifetime, are important in systems where an object holds exclusive access to some resource, and it is desirable to ensure that it releases these resources for use by other objects.
[src:c-book/common-practices] Since C is not an object-oriented language, it has no built-in support for constructors or destructors.
[src:c-book/common-practices] It is not uncommon for clients to explicitly allocate and initialize records and other objects.
[src:c-book/common-practices] However, this leads to a potential for errors, since operations on the object may fail or behave unpredictably if the object is not properly initialized.
[src:c-book/common-practices] Similarly, if it is left to the client to destroy objects correctly, they may fail to do so, causing resource leaks.
[src:c-book/common-practices] It is often useful to combine destructors with *#Nulling freed pointers*.
[src:c-book/common-practices] Sometimes it is useful to hide the definition of the object to ensure that the client does not allocate it manually.
[src:c-book/common-practices] As discussed earlier, after `free()` has been called on a pointer, it becomes a dangling pointer.
[src:c-book/common-practices] Worse still, most modern platforms cannot detect when such a pointer is used before being reassigned.
[src:c-book/common-practices] Unlike dangling pointers, a hardware exception will arise on many modern architectures when a null pointer is dereferenced.
[src:c-book/common-practices] Also, programs can include error checks for the null value, but not for a dangling pointer value.
[src:c-book/common-practices] (To see why the macro is written this way, see *#Macro conventions*.) Also, when this technique is used, destructors should zero out the pointer that they are passed, and their argument must be passed by reference to allow this.
[src:c-book/common-practices] Unfortunately, this idiom will not do anything to any other pointers that may be pointing to the freed memory.
[src:c-book/common-practices] For this reason, some C experts regard this idiom as dangerous due to creating a false sense of security.
[src:c-book/common-practices] Placing parentheses around the entire expression if it is a single expression.
[src:c-book/common-practices] Again, this avoids changes in meaning due to the order of operations.
[src:c-book/common-practices] If a macro produces multiple statements, or declares variables, it can be wrapped in a **do** { ... } **while**(0) loop, with no terminating semicolon.
[src:c-book/common-practices] This allows the macro to be used like a single statement in any location, such as the body of an if statement, while still allowing a semicolon to be placed after the macro invocation without creating a null statement.
[src:c-book/common-practices] Care must be taken that any new variables do not potentially mask portions of the macro's arguments.
[src:c-book/common-practices] Avoiding using a macro argument twice or more inside a macro, if possible; this causes problems with macro arguments that contain side effects, such as assignments.
[src:c-book/common-practices] If a macro may be replaced by a function in the future, considering naming it like a function.
[src:c-book/common-practices] By convention, preprocessor values and macros defined by `#define` are named in all uppercase letters.
[src:c-book/memory-management] In C, you have already considered creating variables for use in the program.
[src:c-book/memory-management] The standard C function `malloc` is the means of implementing dynamic memory allocation.
[src:c-book/memory-management] It is defined in stdlib.h or malloc.h, depending on what operating system you may be using.
[src:c-book/memory-management] Malloc.h contains only the definitions for the memory allocation functions and not the rest of the other functions defined in stdlib.h.
[src:c-book/memory-management] Usually you will not need to be so specific in your program, and if both are supported, you should use <stdlib.h>, since that is ANSI C, and what we will use here.
[src:c-book/memory-management] The corresponding call to release allocated memory back to the operating system is `free`.
[src:c-book/memory-management] When dynamically allocated memory is no longer needed, `free` should be called to release it back to the memory pool.
[src:c-book/memory-management] Overwriting a pointer that points to dynamically allocated memory can result in that data becoming inaccessible.
[src:c-book/memory-management] If this happens frequently, eventually the operating system will no longer be able to allocate more memory for the process.
[src:c-book/memory-management] Once the process exits, the operating system is able to free all dynamically allocated memory associated with the process.
[src:c-book/memory-management] Let's look at how dynamic memory allocation can be used for arrays.
[src:c-book/memory-management] Recall `array` can be considered a pointer which we use as an array.
[src:c-book/memory-management] We specify the length of this array is 10 `int`s.
[src:c-book/memory-management] After `array[0]`, nine other integers have space to be stored consecutively.
[src:c-book/memory-management] Sometimes it is not known at the time the program is written how much memory will be needed for some data; for example, when it depends upon user input.
[src:c-book/memory-management] In this case we would want to dynamically allocate required memory after the program has started executing.
[src:c-book/memory-management] To do this we only need to declare a pointer, and invoke `malloc` when we wish to make space for the elements in our array, *or*, we can tell `malloc` to make space when we first initialize the array.
[src:c-book/memory-management] We also need to know how much an int takes up in memory in order to make room for it; fortunately this is not difficult, we can use C's builtin `sizeof` operator.
[src:c-book/memory-management] For example, if `sizeof(int)` yields 4, then one `int` takes up 4 bytes.
[src:c-book/memory-management] Naturally, `2*sizeof(int)` is how much memory we need for 2 `int`s, and so on.
[src:c-book/memory-management] So how do we `malloc` an array of ten `int`s like before?
[src:c-book/memory-management] We only need to declare the pointer; `malloc` gives us some space to store the 10 `int`s, and returns the pointer to the first element, which is assigned to that pointer.
[src:c-book/memory-management] It is not necessary to immediately call `malloc` after declaring a pointer for the allocated memory.
[src:c-book/memory-management] When we want to use `malloc`, we have to be mindful that the pool of memory available to the programmer is *finite*.
[src:c-book/memory-management] Even if a modern PC will have at least an entire gigabyte of memory, it is still possible and conceivable to run out of it!
[src:c-book/memory-management] In this case, `malloc` will return `NULL`.
[src:c-book/memory-management] Of course, suddenly quitting as in the above example is not always appropriate, and depends on the problem you are trying to solve and the architecture you are programming for.
[src:c-book/memory-management] For example, if the program is a small, non critical application that's running on a desktop quitting may be appropriate.
[src:c-book/memory-management] However if the program is some type of editor running on a desktop, you may want to give the operator the option of saving their tediously entered information instead of just exiting the program.
[src:c-book/memory-management] A memory allocation failure in an embedded processor, such as might be in a washing machine, could cause an automatic reset of the machine.
[src:c-book/memory-management] For this reason, many embedded systems designers avoid dynamic memory allocation altogether.
[src:c-book/memory-management] The `calloc` function allocates space for an array of items and initializes the memory to zeros.
[src:c-book/memory-management] The call `mArray = calloc( count, sizeof(struct V))` allocates `count` objects, each of whose size is sufficient to contain an instance of the structure `struct V`.
[src:c-book/memory-management] The space is initialized to all bits zero.
[src:c-book/memory-management] The function returns either a pointer to the allocated memory or, if the allocation fails, `NULL`.
[src:c-book/memory-management] The `realloc` function changes the size of the object pointed to by `ptr` to the size specified by `size`.
[src:c-book/memory-management] The contents of the object shall be unchanged up to the lesser of the new and old sizes.
[src:c-book/memory-management] If the new size is larger, the value of the newly allocated portion of the object is indeterminate.
[src:c-book/memory-management] If `ptr` is a null pointer, the `realloc` function behaves like the `malloc` function for the specified size.
[src:c-book/memory-management] Otherwise, if `ptr` does not match a pointer earlier returned by the `calloc`, `malloc`, or `realloc` function, or if the space has been deallocated by a call to the `free` or `realloc` function, the behavior is undefined.
[src:c-book/memory-management] If the space cannot be allocated, the object pointed to by `ptr` is unchanged.
[src:c-book/memory-management] If `size` is zero and `ptr` is not a null pointer, the object pointed to is freed.
[src:c-book/memory-management] The `realloc` function returns either a null pointer or a pointer to the possibly moved allocated object.
[src:c-book/memory-management] Memory that has been allocated using `malloc`, `realloc`, or `calloc` must be released back to the system memory pool once it is no longer needed.
[src:c-book/memory-management] This is done to avoid perpetually allocating more and more memory, which could result in an eventual memory allocation failure.
[src:c-book/memory-management] Memory that is not released with `free` is however released when the current program terminates on most operating systems.
[src:c-book/memory-management] Calls to `free` are as in the following example.
[src:c-book/memory-management] It should be noted that `free` is neither intelligent nor recursive.
[src:c-book/memory-management] The following code that depends on the recursive application of free to the internal variables of a struct does not work.
[src:c-book/memory-management] The statement "`free(temp);`" will **not** free `temp->left`, causing a memory leak.
[src:c-book/memory-management] Because C does not have a garbage collector, C programmers are responsible for making sure there is a `free()` exactly once for each time there is a `malloc()`.
[src:c-book/memory-management] If a tree has been allocated one node at a time, then it needs to be freed one node at a time.
[src:c-book/memory-management] Furthermore, using `free` when the pointer in question was never allocated in the first place often crashes or leads to mysterious bugs further along.
[src:c-book/memory-management] To avoid this problem, always initialize pointers when they are declared.
[src:c-book/memory-management] Either use `malloc` at the point they are declared (as in most examples in this chapter), or set them to `NULL` when they are declared (as in the "delayed allocation" example in this chapter).
[src:c-book/memory-management] One way to get memory initialization and destruction right is to imitate object-oriented programming.
[src:c-book/memory-management] In this paradigm, objects are constructed after raw memory is allocated for them, live their lives, and when it is time for them to be destructed, a special function called a destructor destroys the object's innards before the object itself is destroyed.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] A **pointer** is a value that designates the address (i.e., the location in memory), of some value.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] Pointers are variables that hold a memory location.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] Pointers can reference any data type, even functions.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] We'll also discuss the relationship of pointers with text strings and the more advanced concept of function pointers.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] Line 8 declares a variable that points to an int, and line 9 declares a variable that points to something with structure MyStruct.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] So to declare a variable as something that points to some type, rather than contains some type, the asterisk (`*`) is placed before the variable name.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] In the following, line 1 declares `var1` as a pointer to a long and `var2` as a long and not a pointer to a long.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] In line 2, `p3` is declared as a pointer to a pointer to an int.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] Pointer types are often used as parameters to function calls.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] The following shows how to declare a function which uses a pointer as an argument.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] Since C passes function arguments by value, in order to allow a function to modify a value from the calling routine, a pointer to the value must be passed.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] Pointers to structures are also used as function arguments even when nothing in the struct will be modified in the function.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] This is done to avoid copying the complete contents of the structure onto the stack.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] More about pointers as function arguments later.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] So far we've discussed how to declare pointers.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] The process of assigning values to pointers is next.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] To assign the address of a variable to a pointer, the `&` or 'address of' operator is used.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] Here, pPointer will now reference myInt and pKeyboard will reference dvorak.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] Pointers can also be assigned to reference dynamically allocated memory.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] The malloc() and calloc() functions are often used to do this.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] The malloc function returns a pointer to dynamically allocated memory (or NULL if unsuccessful).
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] The size of this memory will be appropriately sized to contain the MyStruct structure.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] The following is an example showing one pointer being assigned to another and of a pointer being assigned a return value from a function.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] When returning a pointer from a function, do not return a pointer that points to a value that is local to the function or that is a pointer to a function argument.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] Pointers to local variables become invalid when the function exits.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] In the above function, the value returned points to a static variable.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] Returning a pointer to dynamically allocated memory is also valid.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] To access a value to which a pointer points, the `*` operator is used.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] Another operator, the `->` operator is used in conjunction with pointers to structures.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] The expression `bb->m_aNumber` is entirely equivalent to `(*bb).m_aNumber`.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] They both access the `m_aNumber` element of the structure pointed to by `bb`.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] There is one more way of dereferencing a pointer, which will be discussed in the following section.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] When dereferencing a pointer that points to an invalid memory location, an error often occurs which results in the program terminating.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] The error is often reported as a segmentation error.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] A common cause of this is failure to initialize a pointer before trying to dereference it.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] C is known for giving you just enough rope to hang yourself, and pointer dereferencing is a prime example.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] You are quite free to write code that accesses memory outside that which you have explicitly requested from the system.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] And many times, that memory may appear as available to your program due to the vagaries of system memory allocation.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] However, even if 99 executions allow your program to run without fault, that 100th execution may be the time when your "memory pilfering" is caught by the system and the program fails.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] Be careful to ensure that your pointer offsets are within the bounds of allocated memory!
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] The declaration `void *somePointer;` is used to declare a pointer of some nonspecified type.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] You can assign a value to a void pointer, but you must cast the variable to point to some specified type before you can dereference it.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] Pointer arithmetic is also not valid with `void *` pointers.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] Up to now, we've carefully been avoiding discussing arrays in the context of pointers.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] The first case often is seen to occur when an array is passed as an argument to a function.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] The function declares the parameter as a pointer, but the actual argument may be the name of an array.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] The second case often occurs when accessing dynamically allocated memory.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] In the following code, the call to `calloc()` effectively allocates an array of struct MyStruct items.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] Pointers and array names can pretty much be used interchangeably; however, there are exceptions.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] You cannot assign a new pointer value to an array name.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] The array name will always point to the first element of the array.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] In the function `returnSameIfAnyEquals`, you could however assign a new value to workingArray, as it is just a pointer to the first element of workingArray.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] It is also valid for a function to return a pointer to one of the array elements from an array passed as an argument to a function.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] A function should never return a pointer to a local variable, even though the compiler will probably not complain.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] When declaring parameters to functions, declaring an array variable without a size is equivalent to declaring a pointer.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] Often this is done to emphasize the fact that the pointer variable will be used in a manner equivalent to an array.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] Now we're ready to discuss pointer arithmetic.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] You can add and subtract integer values to/from pointers.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] If myArray is declared to be some type of array, the expression `*(myArray+j)`, where j is an integer, is equivalent to `myArray[j]`.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] For instance, in the above example where we had the expression `secondArray[i].otherNumber`, we could have written that as `(*(secondArray+i)).otherNumber` or more simply `(secondArray+i)->otherNumber`.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] Note that for addition and subtraction of integers and pointers, the value of the pointer is not adjusted by the integer amount, but is adjusted by the amount multiplied by the size of the type to which the pointer refers in bytes.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] One pointer may also be subtracted from another, provided they point to elements of the same array (or the position just beyond the end of the array).
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] If you have a pointer that points to an element of an array, the index of the element is the result when the array name is subtracted from the pointer.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] You may be wondering how pointers and multidimensional arrays interact.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] Suppose A is declared as a two dimensional array of floats (`float A[D1][D2];`) and that pf is declared a pointer to a float.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] If pf is initialized to point to A[0][0], then *(pf+1) is equivalent to A[0][1] and *(pf+D2) is equivalent to A[1][0].
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] The elements of the array are stored in row-major order.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] Let's look at a slightly different problem.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] We want to have a two dimensional array, but we don't need to have all the rows the same length.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] What we do is declare an array of pointers.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] The second line below declares A as an array of pointers.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] We also note here something curious about array indexing.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] Suppose `myArray` is an array and `i` is an integer value.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] The expression `myArray[i]` is equivalent to `i[myArray]`.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] The first is equivalent to `*(myArray+i)`, and the second is equivalent to `*(i+myArray)`.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] These turn out to be the same, since the addition is commutative.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] Pointers can be used with pre-increment or post-decrement, which is sometimes done within a loop, as in the following example.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] The increment and decrement applies to the pointer, not to the object to which the pointer refers.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] In other words, `*pArray++` is equivalent to `*(pArray++)`.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] Often we need to invoke a function with an argument that is itself a pointer.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] In many instances, the variable is itself a parameter for the current function and may be a pointer to some type of structure.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] The ampersand (**`&`**) character is not needed in this circumstance to obtain a pointer value, as the variable is itself a pointer.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] In the example below, the variable `pStruct`, a pointer, is a parameter to function `FunctTwo`, and is passed as an argument to `FunctOne`.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] The second parameter to `FunctOne` is an int.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] Since in function `FunctTwo`, `mValue` is a pointer to an int, the pointer must first be dereferenced using the * operator, hence the second argument in the call is `*mValue`.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] The third parameter to function `FunctOne` is a pointer to a long.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] Since `pAA` is itself a pointer to a long, no ampersand is needed when it is used as the third argument to the function.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] Historically, text strings in C have been implemented as arrays of characters, with the last byte in the string being a zero, or the null character '\0'.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] Most C implementations come with a standard library of functions for manipulating strings.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] Many of the more commonly used functions expect the strings to be null terminated strings of characters.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] To use these functions requires the inclusion of the standard C header file "string.h".
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] The variable `myFormat` can be viewed as an array of 21 characters.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] There is an implied null character ('\0') tacked on to the end of the string after the 'd' as the 21st item in the array.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] The initialization of an especially long string can be split across lines of source code as follows.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] The library functions that are used with strings are discussed in a later chapter.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] C also allows you to create pointers to functions.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] Pointers to functions syntax can get rather messy.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] Declaring a typedef to a function pointer generally clarifies the code.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] Here's an example that uses a function pointer, and a void * pointer to implement what's known as a callback.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] The `DoSomethingNice` function invokes a caller supplied function `TalkJive` with caller data.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] Note that `DoSomethingNice` really doesn't know anything about what `dataPointer` refers to.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] Some versions of C may not require an ampersand preceding the `TalkJive` argument in the `DoSomethingNice` call.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] Some implementations may require specifically casting the argument to the `MyFunctionType` type, even though the function signature exacly matches that of the typedef.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] Function pointers can be useful for implementing a form of polymorphism in C.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] First one declares a structure having as elements function pointers for the various operations to that can be specified polymorphically.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] A second base object structure containing a pointer to the previous structure is also declared.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] A class is defined by extending the second structure with the data specific for the class, and static variable of the type of the first structure, containing the addresses of the functions that are associated with the class.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] This type of polymorphism is used in the standard library when file I/O functions are called.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] A similar mechanism can also be used for implementing a state machine in C.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] A structure is defined which contains function pointers for handling events that may occur within state, and for functions to be invoked upon entry to and exit from the state.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] An instance of this structure corresponds to a state.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] Each state is initialized with pointers to functions appropriate for the state.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] The current state of the state machine is in effect a pointer to one of these states.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] Changing the value of the current state pointer effectively changes the current state.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] When some event occurs, the appropriate function is called through a function pointer in the current state.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] Function pointers are mainly used to reduce the complexity of switch statement.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] Use to implement this pointer (following code must be placed in library).
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] Below are some example constructs which may aid in creating your pointer.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] The sizeof operator is often used to refer to the size of a static array declared earlier in the same function.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] Note that the `sizeof` operator only works on things defined earlier in the same function.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] The compiler replaces it with some fixed constant number.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] In this case, the `buffer` was declared as an array of 10 char's earlier in the same function, and the compiler replaces `sizeof(buffer)` with the number 10 at compile time (equivalent to us hard-coding 10 into the code in place of `sizeof(buffer)`).
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] The information about the length of `buffer` is not actually stored anywhere in memory (unless we keep track of it separately) and cannot be programmatically obtained at run time from the array/pointer itself.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] Often a function needs to know the size of an array it was given -- an array defined in some other function.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] Unfortunately, (in C and C++) the length of the array cannot be obtained from an array passed in at run time, because (as mentioned above) the size of an array is not stored anywhere.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] The compiler always replaces sizeof with a constant.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] This sum() routine needs to handle more than just one constant length of an array.
[src:c-book/pointers-and-arrays] It's worth mentioning that sizeof operator has two variations: sizeof (*type*) (for instance: sizeof (int) or sizeof (struct some_structure)) and sizeof *expression* (for instance: sizeof some_variable.some_field or sizeof 1).
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] Preprocessors are a way of making text processing with your C program before they are actually compiled.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] Before the actual compilation of every C program it is passed through a Preprocessor.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] The Preprocessor looks through the program trying to find out specific instructions called Preprocessor directives that it can understand.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] All Preprocessor directives begin with the # (hash) symbol.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] C++ compilers use the same C preprocessor.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] The preprocessor is a part of the compiler which performs preliminary operations (conditionally compiling code, including files etc...) to your code before the compiler sees it.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] These transformations are lexical, meaning that the output of the preprocessor is still text.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] Directives are handled by the preprocessor, which is either a separate program invoked by the compiler or part of the compiler itself.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] C has some features as part of the language and some others as part of a **standard library**, which is a repository of code that is available alongside every standard-conformant C compiler.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] When the C compiler compiles your program it usually also links it with the standard C library.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] For example, on encountering a `#include <stdio.h>` directive, it replaces the directive with the contents of the stdio.h header file.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] When you use features from the library, C requires you to *declare* what you would be using.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] The above line causes the C declarations which are in the stdio.h header to be included for use in your program.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] Usually this is implemented by just inserting into your program the contents of a **header file** called stdio.h, located in a system-dependent location.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] The location of such files may be described in your compiler's documentation.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] A list of standard C header files is listed below in the Headers table.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] The stdio.h header contains various declarations for input/output (I/O) using an abstraction of I/O mechanisms called **streams**.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] For example there is an output stream object called stdout which is used to output text to the standard output, which usually displays the text on the computer screen.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] If using angle brackets like the example above, the preprocessor is instructed to search for the include file along the development environment path for the standard includes.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] If you use quotation marks (" "), the preprocessor is expected to search in some additional, usually user-defined, locations for the header file, and to fall back to the standard include paths only if it is not found in those additional locations.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] It is common for this form to include searching in the same directory as the file containing the #include directive.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] The **pragma** (pragmatic information) directive is part of the standard, but the meaning of any pragma depends on the software implementation of the standard that is used.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] The #pragma directive provides a way to request special behavior from the compiler.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] This directive is most useful for programs that are unusually large or that need to take advantage of the capabilities of a particular compiler.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] Pragmas are used within the source program.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] For instance one of the most implemented preprocessor directives, `#pragma once` when placed at the beginning of a header file, indicates that the file where it resides will be skipped if included several times by the preprocessor.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] Each `#define` preprocessor instruction defines a macro.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] A macro defined with a space immediately after the name is called a constant or literal.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] A macro defined with a parenthesis immediately after the name is called a function-like macro.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] The #define directive is used to define macros.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] Macros are used by the preprocessor to manipulate the program source code before it is compiled.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] Because preprocessor macro definitions are substituted before the compiler acts on the source code, any errors that are introduced by #define are difficult to trace.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] By convention, macros defined using #define are named in uppercase.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] Although doing so is not a requirement, it is considered very bad practice to do otherwise.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] This allows the macros to be easily identified when reading the source code.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] (We mention many other common conventions for using `#define` in a later chapter, C Programming/Common practices).
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] Today, #define is primarily used to handle compiler and platform differences.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] E.g., a define might hold a constant which is the appropriate error code for a system call.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] The use of #define should thus be limited unless absolutely necessary; typedef statements and constant variables can often perform the same functions more safely.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] Another feature of the #define command is that it can take arguments, making it rather useful as a pseudo-function creator.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] It's generally a good idea to use extra parentheses when using complex macros.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] Notice that in the above example, the variable "x" is always within its own set of parentheses.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] This way, it will be evaluated in whole, before being compared to 0 or multiplied by -1.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] Also, the entire macro is surrounded by parentheses, to prevent it from being contaminated by other code.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] If you're not careful, you run the risk of having the compiler misinterpret your code.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] Because of side-effects it is considered a very bad idea to use macro functions as described above.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] If ABSOLUTE_VALUE() were a real function 'x' would now have the value of '-9', but because it was an argument in a macro it was expanded twice and thus has a value of -8.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] The **#** and **##** operators are used with the #define macro.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] Using # causes the first argument after the **#** to be returned as a string in quotes.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] Using **##** concatenates what's before the **##** with what's after it.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] which will, of course, display 10 to standard output.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] which will define a function called my_bar().
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] But it isn't possible to integrate a macro argument into a constant string using the concatenation operator.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] In order to obtain such an effect, one can use the ANSI C property that two or more consecutive string constants are considered equivalent to a single string constant when encountered.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] which in turn will be interpreted by the C parser as a single string constant.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] This is a bit tricky, since it is expanded in 2 steps.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] First `num2str(CONST)` is replaced with `str(23)`, which in turn is replaced with `"23"`.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] This will give you a nice debug message including the file and the line where the message was issued.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] If DEBUG is not defined however the debugging message will completely vanish from your code.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] Be careful not to use this sort of construct with anything that has side effects, since this can lead to bugs, that appear and disappear depending on the compilation parameters.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] Macros aren't type-checked and so they do not evaluate arguments.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] Also, they do not obey scope properly, but simply take the string passed to them and replace each occurrence of the macro argument in the text of the macro with the actual string for that parameter (the code is literally copied into the location it was called from).
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] One of the few situations where inline functions won't work -- so you are pretty much forced to use function-like macros instead -- is to initialize compile time constants (static initialization of structs).
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] This happens when the arguments to the macro are literals that the compiler can optimize to another literal.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] The **#error** directive halts compilation.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] When one is encountered the standard specifies that the compiler should emit a diagnostic containing the remaining tokens in the directive.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] This is mostly used for debugging purposes.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] Programmers use "#error" inside a conditional block, to immediately halt the compiler when the "#if" or "#ifdef" -- at the beginning of the block -- detects a compile-time problem.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] Normally the compiler skips the block (and the "#error" directive inside it) and the compilation proceeds.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] Many compilers support a **#warning** directive.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] When one is encountered, the compiler emits a diagnostic containing the remaining tokens in the directive.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] The **#undef** directive undefines a macro.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] The identifier need not have been previously defined.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] The **#if** command checks whether a controlling conditional expression evaluates to zero or nonzero, and excludes or includes a block of code respectively.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] The conditional expression could contain any C operator except for the assignment operators, the increment and decrement operators, the address-of operator, and the sizeof operator.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] One unique operator used in preprocessing and nowhere else is the **defined** operator.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] It returns 1 if the macro name, optionally enclosed in parentheses, is currently defined; 0 if not.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] The **#endif** command ends a block started by `#if`, `#ifdef`, or `#ifndef`.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] The **#elif** command is similar to `#if`, except that it is used to extract one from a series of blocks of code.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] The **#ifdef** command is similar to `#if`, except that the code block following it is selected if a macro name is defined.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] This preprocessor directive is used to set the file name and the line number of the line following the directive to new values.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] This is used to set the __FILE__ and __LINE__ macros.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] Compile-time assertions can help you debug faster than using only run-time assert() statements, because the compile-time assertions are all tested at compile time, while it is possible that a test run of a program may fail to exercise some run-time assert() statements.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] The `static_assert.hpp` Boost library defines a similar macro.
[src:c-book/preprocessor-directives-and-macros] Since C11, such macros are obsolete, as `_Static_assert` and its macro equivalent `static_assert` are standardized and built-in to the language.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] Very few programs follow exactly one control path and have each instruction stated explicitly.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] In order to program effectively, it is necessary to understand how one can alter the steps taken by a program due to user input or other conditions, how some steps can be executed many times with few lines of code, and how programs can appear to demonstrate a rudimentary grasp of logic.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] C constructs known as conditionals and loops grant this power.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] From this point forward, it is necessary to understand what is usually meant by the word *block*.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] A block is a group of code statements that are associated and intended to be executed as a unit.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] In C, the beginning of a block of code is denoted with { (left curly), and the end of a block is denoted with }.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] It is not necessary to place a semicolon after the end of a block.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] Blocks can also be nested; i.e. there can be blocks of code within larger blocks.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] There is likely no meaningful program written in which a computer does not demonstrate basic decision-making skills.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] It can actually be argued that there is no meaningful human activity in which some sort of decision-making, instinctual or otherwise, does not take place.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] A conditional is a statement that instructs the computer to execute a certain block of code or alter certain data only if a specific condition has been met.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] The most common conditional is the If-Else statement, with conditional expressions and Switch-Case statements typically used as more shorthanded methods.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] Before one can understand conditional statements, it is first necessary to understand how C expresses logical relations.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] The value 0 (zero) represents false, and ***all other values*** represent true.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] If you chose some particular value to represent true and then compare values against it, sooner or later your code will fail when your assumed value (often 1) turns out to be incorrect.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] Code written by people uncomfortable with the C language can often be identified by the usage of #define to make a "TRUE" value.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] Because logic is arithmetic in C, arithmetic operators and logical operators are one and the same.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] New programmers should take special note of the fact that the "equal to" operator is ==, not =.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] This is the cause of numerous coding mistakes and is often a difficult-to-find bug, as the expression `(a = b)` sets `a` equal to `b` and subsequently evaluates to `b`; but the expression `(a == b)`, which is usually intended, checks if `a` is equal to `b`.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] It needs to be pointed out that, if you confuse = with ==, your mistake will often not be brought to your attention by the compiler.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] A statement such as `if (c = 20) {}` is considered perfectly valid by the language, but will always assign 20 to `c` and evaluate as true.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] A simple technique to avoid this kind of bug (in many, not all cases) is to put the constant first.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] This will cause the compiler to issue an error, if == got misspelled with =.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] Note that C does not have a dedicated boolean type as many other languages do.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] Often `#define TRUE 1` and `#define FALSE 0` are used to work around the lack of a boolean type.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] This is bad practice, since it makes assumptions that do not hold.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] It is a better idea to indicate what you are actually expecting as a result from a function call, as there are many different ways of indicating error conditions, depending on the situation.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] Here, `strstr` returns the index where the substring foo is found and -1 if it was not found.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] Note: this would always fail with the `TRUE` definition mentioned in the previous paragraph.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] It would also not produce the expected results if we omitted the `>= 0`.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] One other thing to note is that the relational expressions do not evaluate as they would in mathematical texts.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] That is, an expression `myMin < value < myMax` does not evaluate as you probably think it might.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] Mathematically, this would test whether or not *value* is between *myMin* and *myMax*.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] But in C, what happens is that *value* is first compared with *myMin*.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] It is this value that is compared against myMax.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] Because *value* is greater than 0, the first comparison produces a value of 1.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] Now 1 is compared to be less than 10, which is true, so the statements in the if are executed.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] This probably is not what the programmer expected.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] is true (or both), the result is 1, otherwise the result is 0.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] are true, the result is 1, otherwise the result is 0.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] Here's an example of a larger logical expression.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] e is set equal to 1 if a and b are non-zero, or if c is greater than d.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] C uses short circuit evaluation of logical expressions.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] That is to say, once it is able to determine the truth of a logical expression, it does no further evaluation.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] In the snippet of code, the comparison of i with 12 is done first.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] If it evaluates to 0 (false), **i** would be out of bounds as an index to **myArray**.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] In this case, the program never attempts to access **myArray[i]** since the truth of the expression is known to be false.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] Hence we need not worry here about trying to access an out-of-bounds array element if it is already known that i is greater than or equal to zero.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] A similar thing happens with expressions involving the or || operator.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] doThat() is never called if doThis() returns a non-zero (true) value.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] If-Else provides a way to instruct the computer to execute a block of code only if certain conditions have been met.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] The first block of code executes if the condition in parentheses directly after the *if* evaluates to non-zero (true); otherwise, the second block executes.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] The *else* and following block of code are completely optional.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] If there is no need to execute code if a condition is not true, leave it out.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] Also, keep in mind that an *if* can directly follow an *else* statement.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] While this can occasionally be useful, chaining more than two or three if-elses in this fashion is considered bad programming practice.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] We can get around this with the Switch-Case construct described later.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] Two other general syntax notes need to be made that you will also see in other control constructs: First, note that there is no semicolon after *if* or *else*.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] There could be, but the block (code enclosed in { and }) takes the place of that.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] Second, if you only intend to execute one statement as a result of an *if* or *else*, curly braces are not needed.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] However, many programmers believe that inserting curly braces anyway in this case is good coding practice.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] The following code sets a variable c equal to the greater of two variables a and b, or 0 if a and b are equal.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] Most importantly, if your conditionals are not mutually exclusive, *two* cases could execute instead of only one.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] If the code was different and the value of a or b changes somehow (e.g.: you reset the lesser of a and b to 0 after the comparison) during one of the blocks?
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] You could end up with multiple *if* statements being invoked, which is not your intent.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] Also, evaluating *if* conditionals takes processor time.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] If you use *else* to handle these situations, in the case above assuming (a > b) is non-zero (true), the program is spared the expense of evaluating additional *if* statements.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] The bottom line is that it is usually best to insert an *else* clause for all cases in which a conditional will not evaluate to non-zero (true).
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] A conditional expression is a way to set values conditionally in a more shorthand fashion than If-Else.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] If it is non-zero (true), the overall conditional expression evaluates to the expression placed between the ? and :, otherwise, it evaluates to the expression after the :.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] Conditional expressions can sometimes clarify the intent of the code.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] Nesting the conditional operator should usually be avoided.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] It's best to use conditional expressions only when the expressions for a and b are simple.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] Also, contrary to a common beginner belief, conditional expressions do not make for faster code.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] As tempting as it is to assume that fewer lines of code result in faster execution times, there is no such correlation.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] Say you write a program where the user inputs a number 1-5 (corresponding to student grades, A(represented as 1)-D(4) and F(5)), stores it in a variable **grade** and the program responds by printing to the screen the associated letter grade.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] Having a long chain of if-else-if-else-if-else can be a pain, both for the programmer and anyone reading the code.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] The Switch-Case construct takes a variable, placed after *switch*, and compares it to the value following the *case* keyword.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] If the variable is equal to the value specified after *case*, the construct "activates", or begins executing the code after the case statement.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] Once the construct has "activated", there will be no further evaluation of *case*s.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] Switch-Case is syntactically "weird" in that no braces are required for code associated with a *case*.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] If a *default* case is specified, the associated statements are executed if none of the other cases match.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] Here's a switch statement that corresponds to the sequence of if - else if statements above.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] A set of statements to execute can be grouped with more than one value of the variable as in the following example.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] Often in computer programming, it is necessary to perform a certain action a certain number of times or until a certain condition is met.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] It is impractical and tedious to simply type a certain statement or group of statements a large number of times, not to mention that this approach is too inflexible and unintuitive to be counted on to stop when a certain event has happened.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] As a real-world analogy, someone asks a dishwasher at a restaurant what he did all night.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] He will respond, "I washed dishes all night long." He is not likely to respond, "I washed a dish, then washed a dish, then washed a dish, then...".
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] The constructs that enable computers to perform certain repetitive tasks are called loops.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] A while loop is the most basic type of loop.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] It will run as long as the condition is non-zero (true).
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] For example, if you try the following, the program will appear to lock up and you will have to manually close the program down.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] A situation where the conditions for exiting the loop will never become true is called an infinite loop.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] Here is another example of a while loop.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] It prints out all the powers of two less than 100.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] The flow of all loops can also be controlled by **break** and **continue** statements.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] A break statement will immediately exit the enclosing loop.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] A continue statement will skip the remainder of the block and start at the controlling conditional statement again.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] In this example, the computer prints the value of a as usual, and prints a notice that a is not 64 (unless it was skipped by the continue statement).
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] This will merely increase a until a is not less than 100.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] When the computer reaches the end of the while loop, it always goes back to the while statement at the top of the loop, where it re-evaluates the controlling condition.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] If that condition is "true" at that instant -- even if it was temporarily 0 for a few statements inside the loop -- then the computer begins executing the statements inside the loop again; otherwise the computer exits the loop.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] The computer does not "continuously check" the controlling condition of a while loop during the execution of that loop.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] It only "peeks" at the controlling condition each time it reaches the `while` at the top of the loop.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] It is very important to note, once the controlling condition of a While loop becomes 0 (false), the loop will not terminate until the block of code is finished and it is time to reevaluate the conditional.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] If you need to terminate a While loop immediately upon reaching a certain condition, consider using **break**.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] This executes the code in the while loop 5 times, with i having values that range from 4 down to 0 (inside the loop).
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] Conveniently, these are the values needed to access every item of an array containing 5 elements.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] The *initialization* statement is executed exactly once - before the first evaluation of the *test* condition.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] Typically, it is used to assign an initial value to some variable, although this is not strictly necessary.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] The *initialization* statement can also be used to declare and initialize variables used in the loop.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] The *test* expression is evaluated each time before the code in the *for* loop executes.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] If this expression evaluates as 0 (false) when it is checked (i.e. if the expression is not true), the loop is not (re)entered and execution continues normally at the code immediately following the FOR-loop.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] If the expression is non-zero (true), the code within the braces of the loop is executed.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] After each iteration of the loop, the *increment* statement is executed.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] This often is used to increment the loop index for the loop, the variable initialized in the initialization expression and tested in the test expression.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] Following this statement execution, control returns to the top of the loop, where the *test* action occurs.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] If a *continue* statement is executed within the *for* loop, the increment statement would be the next one executed.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] Each of these parts of the for statement is optional and may be omitted.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] Because of the free-form nature of the for statement, some fairly fancy things can be done with it.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] Often a for loop is used to loop through items in an array, processing each item at a time.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] The above for loop initializes each of the 12 elements of myArray.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] The loop index can start from any value.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] You will most often use loop indexes that start from 0, since arrays are indexed at zero, but you will sometimes use other values to initialize a loop index as well.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] The *increment* action can do other things, such as *decrement*.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] Here's an example where the test condition is simply a variable.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] If the variable has a value of 0 or NULL, the loop exits, otherwise the statements in the body of the loop are executed.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] A WHILE loop can be used to do the same thing as a FOR loop, however a FOR loop is a more condensed way to perform a set number of repetitions since all of the necessary information is in a one line statement.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] This is called an infinite loop since it will loop forever unless there is a break statement within the statements of the for loop.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] The empty test condition effectively evaluates as true.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] It is also common to use the comma operator in for loops to execute multiple statements.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] Special care should be taken when designing or refactoring the conditional part, especially whether using < or <= , whether start and stop should be corrected by 1, and in case of prefix- and postfix-notations.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] A DO-WHILE loop is a post-check while loop, which means that it checks the condition after each run.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] As a result, even if the condition is zero (false), it will run at least once.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] Since this is also a type of while loop, **break** and **continue** statements within the loop function accordingly.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] A **continue** statement causes a jump to the test of the condition and a *break* statement exits the loop.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] It is worth noting that Do-While and While are functionally almost identical, with one important difference: Do-While loops are always guaranteed to execute at least once, but While loops will not execute at all if their condition is 0 (false) on the first evaluation.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] The ability to transfer the flow of control enabled by gotos is so powerful that, in addition to the simple if, all other control constructs can be written using gotos instead.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] Here, the first goto is conditional on the value of "cond".
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] As these cases demonstrate, often the structure of what your program is doing can usually be expressed without using gotos.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] Undisciplined use of gotos can create unreadable, unmaintainable code when more idiomatic alternatives (such as if-elses, or for loops) can better express your structure.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] Theoretically, the goto construct does not ever *have* to be used, but there are cases when it can increase readability, avoid code duplication, or make control variables unnecessary.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] You should consider first mastering the idiomatic solutions, and use goto only when necessary.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] Keep in mind that many, if not most, C style guidelines *strictly forbid* use of **goto**, with the only common exceptions being the following examples.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] One use of goto is to break out of a deeply nested loop.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] Since **break** will not work (it can only escape one loop), **goto** can be used to jump completely outside the loop.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] Breaking outside of deeply nested loops without the use of the goto is always possible, but often involves the creation and testing of extra variables that may make the resulting code far less readable than it would be with **goto**.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] The use of **goto** makes it easy to undo actions in an orderly fashion, typically to avoid failing to free memory that had been allocated.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] Another accepted use is the creation of a state machine.
[src:c-book/program-flow-control] This is a fairly advanced topic though, and not commonly needed.
[src:c-book/standard-libraries] The **C standard library** is a standardized collection of header files and library routines used to implement common operations, such as input/output and character string handling.
[src:c-book/standard-libraries] Unlike other languages (such as COBOL, Fortran, and PL/I) C does not include built in keywords for these tasks, so nearly all C programs rely on the standard library to operate.
[src:c-book/standard-libraries] The C programming language previously did not provide any elementary functions, such as I/O operations.
[src:c-book/standard-libraries] Over time, user communities of C shared ideas and implementations to provide those functions.
[src:c-book/standard-libraries] These ideas became common, and were eventually incorporated into the definition of the standardized C programming language in 1989.
[src:c-book/standard-libraries] These are now called the **C standard libraries**.
[src:c-book/standard-libraries] Both Unix and C were created at AT&T's Bell Laboratories in the late 1960s and early 1970s.
[src:c-book/standard-libraries] During the 1970s the C programming language became increasingly popular, with many universities and organizations beginning to create their own variations of the language for their own projects.
[src:c-book/standard-libraries] By the start of the 1980s compatibility problems between the various C implementations became apparent.
[src:c-book/standard-libraries] In 1983 the American National Standards Institute (ANSI) formed a committee to establish a standard specification of C known as "ANSI C".
[src:c-book/standard-libraries] This work culminated in the creation of the so-called **C89** standard in 1989.
[src:c-book/standard-libraries] Part of the resulting standard was a set of software libraries called the **ANSI C standard library**.
[src:c-book/standard-libraries] Later revisions of the C standard have added several new required header files to the library.
[src:c-book/standard-libraries] Support for these new extensions varies between implementations.
[src:c-book/standard-libraries] The headers **<iso646.h>**, **<wchar.h>**, and **<wctype.h>** were added with Normative Addendum 1 (hereafter abbreviated as **NA1**), an addition to the C Standard ratified in 1995.
[src:c-book/standard-libraries] The declaration of each function is kept in a header file, while the actual implementation of functions are separated into a library file.
[src:c-book/standard-libraries] The naming and scope of headers have become common but the organization of libraries still remains diverse.
[src:c-book/standard-libraries] The standard library is usually shipped along with a compiler.
[src:c-book/standard-libraries] Since C compilers often provide extra functions that are not specified in ANSI C, a standard library with a particular compiler is mostly incompatible with standard libraries of other compilers.
[src:c-book/standard-libraries] Much of the C standard library has been shown to have been well-designed.
[src:c-book/standard-libraries] A few parts, with the benefit of hindsight, are regarded as mistakes.
[src:c-book/standard-libraries] The string input functions `gets()` (and the use of `scanf()` to read string input) are the source of many buffer overflows, and most programming guides recommend avoiding this usage.
[src:c-book/standard-libraries] Another oddity is `strtok()`, a function that is designed as a primitive lexical analyser but is highly "fragile" and difficult to use.
[src:c-book/standard-libraries] The ANSI C standard library consists of 24 C header files which can be included into a programmer's project with a single directive.
[src:c-book/standard-libraries] Each header file contains one or more function declarations, data type definitions and macros.
[src:c-book/standard-libraries] The contents of these header files follows.
[src:c-book/standard-libraries] In comparison to some other languages (for example Java) the standard library is minuscule.
[src:c-book/standard-libraries] The library provides a basic set of mathematical functions, string manipulation, type conversions, and file and console-based I/O.
[src:c-book/standard-libraries] It does not include a standard set of "container types" like the C++ Standard Template Library, let alone the complete graphical user interface (GUI) toolkits, networking tools, and profusion of other functions that Java provides as standard.
[src:c-book/standard-libraries] The main advantage of the small standard library is that providing a working ANSI C environment is much easier than it is with other languages, and consequently porting C to a new platform is relatively easy.
[src:c-book/standard-libraries] Many other libraries have been developed to supply equivalent functions to that provided by other languages in their standard library.
[src:c-book/standard-libraries] For instance, the GNOME desktop environment project has developed the GTK+ graphics toolkit and GLib, a library of container data structures, and there are many other well-known examples.
[src:c-book/standard-libraries] The variety of libraries available has meant that some superior toolkits have proven themselves through history.
[src:c-book/standard-libraries] The considerable downside is that they often do not work particularly well together, programmers are often familiar with different sets of libraries, and a different set of them may be available on any particular platform.
[src:c-book/standard-libraries] While not standardized, C programs may depend on a runtime library of routines which contain code the compiler uses at runtime.
[src:c-book/standard-libraries] The code that initializes the process for the operating system, for example, before calling `main()`, is implemented in the C Run-Time Library for a given vendor's compiler.
[src:c-book/standard-libraries] The Run-Time Library code might help with other language feature implementations, like handling uncaught exceptions or implementing floating point code.
[src:c-book/standard-libraries] The C standard library only documents that the specific routines mentioned in this article are available, and how they behave.
[src:c-book/standard-libraries] Though often confused with the C Standard Library because of this packaging, the C Runtime Library is not a standardized part of the language and is vendor-specific.
[src:c-book/standard-libraries] POSIX, (along with the Single Unix Specification), specifies a number of routines that should be available over and above those in the C standard library proper; these are often implemented alongside the C standard library functions, with varying degrees of closeness.
[src:c-book/standard-libraries] For example, glibc implements functions such as fork within libc.so, but before NPTL was merged into glibc it constituted a separate library with its own linker flag.
[src:c-book/standard-libraries] Often, this POSIX-specified function will be regarded as part of the library; the C library proper may be identified as the ANSI or ISO C library.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] A **string** in C is merely an array of characters.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] The length of a string is determined by a terminating null character: `'\0'`.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] So, a string with the contents, say, `"abc"` has four characters: `'a'`, `'b'`, `'c'`, and the terminating null (`'\0'`) character.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] The terminating null character has the value zero.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] In C, string constants (literals) are surrounded by double quotes ("), e.g.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] "Hello world!" and are compiled to an array of the specified char values with an additional null terminating character (0-valued) code to mark the end of the string.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] The type of a string constant is char [].
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] String literals may not directly in the source code contain embedded newlines or other control characters, or some other characters of special meaning in string.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] C supports wide character strings, defined as arrays of the type wchar_t, 16-bit (at least) values.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] This feature allows strings where more than 256 different possible characters are needed (although also variable length char strings can be used).
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] These strings are not supported by the <string.h> functions.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] Instead they have their own functions, declared in <wchar.h>.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] What character encoding the char and wchar_t represent is not specified by the C standard, except that the value 0x00 and 0x0000 specify the end of the string and not a character.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] It is the input and output code which are directly affected by the character encoding.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] The editor should also be able to handle the encoding if strings shall be able to be written in the source code.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] Because programmers find raw strings cumbersome to deal with, they wrote the code in the `<string.h>` library.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] It represents not a concerted design effort but rather the accretion of contributions made by various authors over a span of years.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] Other functions, such as `strlwr` (convert to lower case), `strrev` (return the string reversed), and `strupr` (convert to upper case) may be popular; however, they are neither specified by the C Standard nor the Single Unix Standard.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] It is also unspecified whether these functions return copies of the original strings or convert the strings in place.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] The `strcat()` function shall append a copy of the string pointed to by `s2` (including the terminating null byte) to the end of the string pointed to by `s1`.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] The initial byte of `s2` overwrites the null byte at the end of `s1`.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] If copying takes place between objects that overlap, the behavior is undefined.
