[src:c-book/string-manipulation] A rudimentary form of string comparison is done with the strcmp() function.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] It takes two strings as arguments and returns a value less than zero if the first is lexographically less than the second, a value greater than zero if the first is lexographically greater than the second, or zero if the two strings are equal.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] The comparison is done by comparing the coded (ascii) value of the characters, character by character.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] This simple type of string comparison is nowadays generally considered unacceptable when sorting lists of strings.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] More advanced algorithms exist that are capable of producing lists in dictionary sorted order.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] They can also fix problems such as strcmp() considering the string "Alpha2" greater than "Alpha12".
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] (In the previous example, "Alpha2" compares greater than "Alpha12" because '2' comes after '1' in the character set.) What we're saying is, don't use this `strcmp()` alone for general string sorting in any commercial or professional code.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] The `strcmp()` function shall compare the string pointed to by `s1` to the string pointed to by `s2`.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] The sign of a non-zero return value shall be determined by the sign of the difference between the values of the first pair of bytes (both interpreted as type `unsigned char`) that differ in the strings being compared.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] Upon completion, `strcmp()` shall return an integer greater than, equal to, or less than 0, if the string pointed to by `s1` is greater than, equal to, or less than the string pointed to by `s2`, respectively.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] Since comparing pointers by themselves is not practically useful unless one is comparing pointers within the same array, this function lexically compares the strings that two pointers point to.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] This function is useful in comparisons, e.g.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] The collating sequence used by `strcmp()` is equivalent to the machine's native character set.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] The only guarantee about the order is that the digits from '0' to '9' are in consecutive order.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] The `strcpy()` function shall copy the C string pointed to by `s2` (including the terminating null byte) into the array pointed to by `s1`.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] There is no value used to indicate an error: if the arguments to `strcpy()` are correct, and the destination buffer is large enough, the function will never fail.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] Important: You must ensure that the destination buffer (`s1`) is able to contain all the characters in the source array, including the terminating null byte.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] Otherwise, `strcpy()` will overwrite memory past the end of the buffer, causing a buffer overflow, which can cause the program to crash, or can be exploited by hackers to compromise the security of the computer.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] The `strlen()` function shall compute the number of bytes in the string to which `s` points, not including the terminating null byte.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] It returns the number of bytes in the string.
