[src:c-book/string-manipulation] The function shall return s1; no return value is reserved to indicate an error.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] It is possible that the function will **not** return a null-terminated string, which happens if the `s2` string is longer than `n` bytes.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] The `strrchr` function is similar to the `strchr` function, except that `strrchr` returns a pointer to the **last** occurrence of `c` within `s` instead of the first.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] The `strrchr()` function shall locate the last occurrence of `c` (converted to a `char`) in the string pointed to by `s`.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] Its return value is similar to `strchr`'s return value.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] At one point in history, this function was named `rindex`.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] The `strrchr` name, however cryptic, fits the general pattern for naming.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] The `memcpy()` function shall copy `n` bytes from the object pointed to by `s2` into the object pointed to by `s1`.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] Because the function does not have to worry about overlap, it can do the simplest copy it can.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] The `memmove()` function shall copy `n` bytes from the object pointed to by `s2` into the object pointed to by `s1`.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] Copying takes place as if the `n` bytes from the object pointed to by `s2` are first copied into a temporary array of `n` bytes that does not overlap the objects pointed to by `s1` and `s2`, and then the `n` bytes from the temporary array are copied into the object pointed to by `s1`.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] The easy way to implement this without using a temporary array is to check for a condition that would prevent an ascending copy, and if found, do a descending copy.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] The `memcmp()` function shall compare the first `n` bytes (each interpreted as `unsigned char`) of the object pointed to by `s1` to the first `n` bytes of the object pointed to by `s2`.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] The sign of a non-zero return value shall be determined by the sign of the difference between the values of the first pair of bytes (both interpreted as type `unsigned char`) that differ in the objects being compared.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] The ANSI C Standard specifies two locale-specific comparison functions.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] The `strcoll` function compares the string pointed to by `s1` to the string pointed to by `s2`, both interpreted as appropriate to the `LC_COLLATE` category of the current locale.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] The return value is similar to `strcmp`.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] The `strxfrm` function transforms the string pointed to by `s2` and places the resulting string into the array pointed to by `s1`.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] The transformation is such that if the `strcmp` function is applied to the two transformed strings, it returns a value greater than, equal to, or less than zero, corresponding to the result of the `strcoll` function applied to the same two original strings.
