[src:c-book/string-manipulation] The `strstr()` function shall locate the first occurrence in the string pointed to by `haystack` of the sequence of bytes (excluding the terminating null byte) in the string pointed to by `needle`.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] The function returns the pointer to the matching string in `haystack` or a null pointer if a match is not found.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] If `needle` is an empty string, the function returns `haystack`.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] A sequence of calls to `strtok()` breaks the string pointed to by `s1` into a sequence of tokens, each of which is delimited by a byte from the string pointed to by `delimiters`.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] The first call in the sequence has `s1` as its first argument, and is followed by calls with a null pointer as their first argument.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] The separator string pointed to by `delimiters` may be different from call to call.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] The first call in the sequence searches the string pointed to by `s1` for the first byte that is not contained in the current separator string pointed to by `delimiters`.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] If no such byte is found, then there are no tokens in the string pointed to by `s1` and `strtok()` shall return a null pointer.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] If such a byte is found, it is the start of the first token.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] The `strtok()` function then searches from there for a byte (or multiple, consecutive bytes) that is contained in the current separator string.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] If no such byte is found, the current token extends to the end of the string pointed to by `s1`, and subsequent searches for a token shall return a null pointer.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] If such a byte is found, it is overwritten by a null byte, which terminates the current token.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] The `strtok()` function saves a pointer to the following byte, from which the next search for a token shall start.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] Each subsequent call, with a null pointer as the value of the first argument, starts searching from the saved pointer and behaves as described above.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] The `strtok()` function need not be reentrant.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] A function that is not required to be reentrant is not required to be thread-safe.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] Because the `strtok()` function must save state between calls, and you could not have two tokenizers going at the same time, the Single Unix Standard defined a similar function, `strtok_r()`, that does not need to save state.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] The `strtok_r()` function considers the null-terminated string `s` as a sequence of zero or more text tokens separated by spans of one or more characters from the separator string `delimiters`.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] The argument lasts points to a user-provided pointer which points to stored information necessary for `strtok_r()` to continue scanning the same string.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] In the first call to `strtok_r()`, `s` points to a null-terminated string, `delimiters` to a null-terminated string of separator characters, and the value pointed to by `lasts` is ignored.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] The `strtok_r()` function shall return a pointer to the first character of the first token, write a null character into `s` immediately following the returned token, and update the pointer to which `lasts` points.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] In subsequent calls, `s` is a null pointer and `lasts` shall be unchanged from the previous call so that subsequent calls shall move through the string `s`, returning successive tokens until no tokens remain.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] The separator string `delimiters` may be different from call to call.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] When no token remains in `s`, a NULL pointer shall be returned.
[src:c-book/string-manipulation] These functions do not fit into one of the above categories.
